#
# kobalt CLI surface (decoded from Args.kt @Parameter decls):
#   targets...                  positional list of build targets
#   -bf / --buildFile FILE      build file (default: kobalt/src/Build.kt)
#   -i / --init TEMPLATES       invoke named templates, comma-separated
#   --checkVersions             check newer dependency versions
#   --client                    run as client (connect to existing server)
#   --dev                       turn on dev mode (more verbose log)
#   --download                  force download from wrapper downloadUrl
#   --downloadSources           force download of sources and javadocs
#   --dryRun                    display tasks without running them
#   --force                     force new server even if one is running
#   --gc                        delete old files
#   --help / --usage            display help (multi-long-name alias)
#   --listTemplates             list available templates
#   --log LEVEL                 log level (Int 0-3)
#   --logTags TAGS              comma-separated tags to enable logging for
#   --forceIncremental          force incremental even if build file modified
#   --noIncremental             turn off incremental builds
#   --noIncrementalKotlin       disable incremental Kotlin compilation
#   --offline                   no dependency downloads
#   --plugins IDS               comma-separated Maven plugin IDs
#   --pluginJarFiles FILES      comma-separated plugin jar files
#   --port PORT                 port for --server
#   --profiles PROFILES         comma-separated profiles to run
#   --profiling                 display task timings at end of build
#   --projectInfo               display current project info
#   --resolve DEPENDENCY        resolve dependency and display tree
#   --sequential                build all projects in sequence
#   --server                    run in server mode
#   --tasks                     display available tasks
#   --update                    update to latest Kobalt
#   --version                   display version
#
# kobalt is a Kotlin-based build system for the
# JVM, authored by **Cédric Beust** (TestNG
# author + JCommander author — so kobalt's CLI
# is JCommander's CANONICAL real-world use case
# by the library's own author).  437 GH stars.
# Sister tools: gradle (Groovy-based JVM build
# system, in corpus), maven (XML-based JVM
# build, in corpus), sbt (Scala build, in corpus),
# ant (in corpus).  Kobalt aimed to be more
# Kotlin-idiomatic than Gradle.
#
# Critical extraction note: kobalt uses **Java/
# Kotlin `JCommander` library** at Main.kt:3 +
# Args.kt — corpus's **first documented
# JCommander library** + **second documented Java
# CLI library** (joining R276 picocli).
# JCommander (com.beust:jcommander, Maven Central)
# was created by Cédric Beust in 2010 as a JSR-
# 310-influenced replacement for Apache Commons
# CLI.  Distinct from R276 picocli (auto-generated
# usage tables, more annotations, ANSI color
# support) by Remko Popma — picocli has overtaken
# JCommander in popularity since ~2018 but
# JCommander remains widely used in legacy Java
# projects.  Distinct from Apache Commons CLI
# (older, more verbose), args4j (Kohsuke Kawaguchi
# — Jenkins author).  Extends cross-language CLI
# taxonomy to SIXTY-ONE library variants: Rust (6),
# Go (4), Python (3), Crystal 1 OptionParser
# (R269), Haskell (R270), OCaml (R271), C (R272),
# **Java 1 picocli (R276)**, Kotlin (R277),
# Scala (R278), Dart (R279), Ruby (R280),
# Perl (R281), PHP (R282), Swift (R283),
# F# (R284), Lua (R285), C# (R286), Nim 1
# parseopt (R287), Zig (R288), D (R289),
# Racket (R290), Common Lisp 1 (R291),
# Erlang (R292), Tcl (R293), Pharo Smalltalk (R294),
# Common Lisp 2 clingon (R295), Julia (R296),
# SWI-Prolog optparse (R297), Pony stdlib cli (R298),
# Crystal 2 Admiral (R299), V stdlib `flag` (R300),
# Nim 2 cligen (R301), Clojure 1 babashka.cli
# (R302), Gleam Glint (R303), Ada GNAT.Command_
# Line (R304), C++ 1 CLI11 (R305), Elixir Optimus
# (R306), Vala GLib.OptionContext (R307), Hare
# stdlib getopt (R308), Standard ML stdlib GetOpt
# (R309), Fortran M_CLI2 (R310), Guile (ice-9
# getopt-long) (R311), Free Pascal TCustomApplication
# (R312), Idris 2 System.GetOpts (R313), Mercury
# stdlib getopt_io (R314), Eiffel Gobo AP_PARSER
# (R315), C++ 2 boost::program_options (R316),
# Forth/Gforth `next-arg` (R317), Clojure 2
# org.clojure/tools.cli (R318), Roc weaver (R319),
# Chapel `config` keyword (R320), Mojo `alias`-
# as-spec (R321), **Java 2 JCommander** (R322 —
# NEW).  **MAJOR PATTERN MILESTONE**: 61 cross-
# language CLI library variants documented.  Java
# joins the multi-library club (after Rust 6, Go
# 4, Python 3, Crystal 2, Common Lisp 2, Nim 2,
# Clojure 2, C++ 2): TWO Java CLI library
# variants now documented (picocli + JCommander).
#
# Critical extraction note: kobalt uses **JCommander
# field-annotation-as-spec pattern** at Args.kt
# (whole file) — `class Args { @Parameter ... }`
# annotates fields with `@Parameter` directly.
# The CLASS itself becomes the SPEC; the parser
# uses reflection to discover all annotated
# fields.  Distinct from R276 picocli `@Command
# class` + `@Option` + `@Parameters` (split
# annotations), R305 C++ CLI11 (struct + add_
# option method-chain), R270 Haskell `Option`
# constructor list, R311 Guile quoted-assoc-list.
# JCommander's approach: SINGLE `@Parameter`
# annotation for both options AND positionals —
# corpus's **first documented unified-annotation-
# for-options-and-positionals CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: kobalt uses **JCommander
# bare-`@Parameter`-as-positional CLI pattern**
# at Args.kt:8 — `@Parameter var targets: List
# <String> = arrayListOf()` declares the POSITIONAL
# ARGS field by OMITTING the `names` parameter.
# All non-flag argv tokens accumulate into this
# field.  Distinct from R276 picocli `@Parameters`
# (different annotation), R305 C++ CLI11
# positional-name-without-leading-dash, R307 Vala
# GLib empty-string-name OptionEntry sentinel,
# R316 C++ boost positional_options_description
# with `.add("name", -1)` mapping.  JCommander's
# approach: BARE `@Parameter` WITH NO `names` =
# POSITIONAL — corpus's **first documented
# bare-annotation-as-positional CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: kobalt uses **JCommander
# array-of-strings-for-all-names CLI pattern** at
# Args.kt:11+ — `@Parameter(names = arrayOf("-bf",
# "--buildFile"), ...)` packs SHORT AND LONG
# NAMES into the same `String[]` array, with no
# short-vs-long type distinction.  Distinct from
# R316 C++ boost `"help,h"` comma-string (also
# packs but separated by comma), R270 Haskell
# `Option [Char] [String]` two-list (separate
# short-char-list and long-string-list), R313
# Idris 2 `['?', 'h']` Char-list + `["help"]`
# String-list (same separation).  JCommander's
# approach: SINGLE ARRAY of STRINGS for ALL
# names — the parser distinguishes short from
# long by the number of leading dashes in each
# entry.  Corpus's **first documented array-of-
# strings-for-all-names CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: kobalt uses **JCommander
# multi-long-name array aliases** at Args.kt:45
# — `@Parameter(names = arrayOf("--help",
# "--usage"), ...)` declares MULTIPLE LONG-NAME
# aliases for the same field.  Distinct from R309
# SML `short = "vV"` (string-of-chars for multi-
# short — but SHORTS only), R313 Idris 2
# `["help", "halp"]` long-string-list-aliases
# (multi-longs in a separate list).  JCommander
# supports MULTIPLE LONG-NAME aliases by listing
# them in the SAME `names = arrayOf(...)` array —
# corpus's **first documented multi-long-name-
# array CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: kobalt uses **JCommander
# reflection-based-type-conversion CLI pattern**
# at Args.kt:52+ — `var log: Int = Constants.LOG_
# DEFAULT_LEVEL` — JCommander auto-detects the
# field's TYPE via reflection (`Int`, `Boolean`,
# `String?`, `List<String>`) and converts the
# argv value accordingly.  No explicit `:parse-fn`
# or converter needed for primitives.  Distinct
# from R311 Guile `(value #t)` (boolean-or-symbol
# arg-shape), R313 Idris 2 `ReqArg Input "<file>"`
# (constructor variant), R318 Clojure tools.cli
# `:parse-fn` (explicit transformer).  JCommander's
# approach: TYPE-DRIVEN AUTO-CONVERSION via
# reflection — corpus's **first documented
# reflection-based-type-conversion CLI pattern**.
# For complex types, JCommander supports
# `converter = XYZ.class` (used by sister tool
# moditect for `Path` and `Instant` types).
#
# Critical extraction note: kobalt uses **Kotlin
# companion-object-constant-in-annotation CLI
# pattern** at Args.kt:92-95 — `companion object {
# const val SEQUENTIAL = "--sequential" }` then
# `@Parameter(names = arrayOf(Args.SEQUENTIAL),
# ...)`.  Kotlin's `companion object` constants
# are COMPILE-TIME-VISIBLE INSIDE annotations
# (Kotlin compiler resolves the reference at
# annotation-processing time).  Distinct from
# R276 picocli (no companion-object pattern in
# Java), R305 C++ CLI11 (#define or static const).
# Corpus's **first documented companion-object-
# constant-in-annotation CLI pattern**.
#
# Hunt-skip notes: skipped `_picocli` (would
# refer to the LIBRARY itself, not a CLI),
# `_gradle` / `_maven` / `_sbt` / `_ant` (JVM
